  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This dataset, published in 2015 on the DRYAD repository by a team from Virginia Tech, investigates the effects of hunting and habitat loss on native carnivore communities in Madagascar. With a notable download count of 70 and a total of 421 views, it demonstrates active engagement and interest within the research community.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The dataset titled \"Hunting, exotic carnivores, and habitat loss: anthropogenic effects on a native carnivore community, Madagascar\" serves as a vital resource in examining the ecological impact of human activities on wildlife. Published in DRYAD in 2015 by authors including Zach J. Farris and Asia Murphy, this dataset has garnered a total of 421 views and 70 downloads, indicating a strong interest and potential application among researchers in the field.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The commitment to open data is reflected in the inclusion of this dataset in a reputable data repository, DRYAD, which enhances its accessibility to the scientific community. This level of transparency underscores the importance of sharing research findings to facilitate further studies and collaborative efforts. The dataset has been referenced once in the academic literature, notably in a preprint published in Research Square, illustrating its influence on ongoing discourse within the subject area.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Additionally, the dataset has proven to be a foundational resource for subsequent research, as evidenced by its downstream reuse in at least two other studies. This impact highlights the dataset's role in advancing understanding of anthropogenic effects on biodiversity, particularly in vulnerable ecosystems like those found in Madagascar.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Overall, the dataset exemplifies effective scientific stewardship and engagement in ecological research. The authors' affiliation with Virginia Tech lends credibility to the findings and enhances their relevance in conservation biology discussions, continuing to resonate with researchers across regions such as the United Kingdom and Kenya, which are among the top citing countries. This geographical diversity further illustrates the global significance of the issues investigated in this dataset.</p>",
